      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. u mentioned nutrient deficiency... could it specifically be nitrogen? also i'm not seeing any bugs or anything on the leaves, just the yellowing. how do i tell if the soil ph is the reason they arent getting enough nutrients?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the possibility of a nitrogen deficiency is indeed a common culprit behind the yellowing of lower leaves in tomato plants. Nitrogen is a crucial nutrient for plant growth, and its deficiency can lead to the symptoms you're observing. To determine if the soil pH is affecting nutrient availability, you'll want to test the soil pH. Most plants, including tomatoes, thrive in slightly acidic soil with a pH between 6.0 and 7.0. If the pH is outside this range, it could be hindering the plants' ability to absorb nutrients effectively. You can purchase a soil pH testing kit from a garden center or online. Once you have the results, you can adjust the soil pH by adding lime to raise it or sulfur to lower it, depending on the needs of your tomato plants. Remember, the key to a happy garden is balance, so don't overdo it with any amendments. Happy gardening!",
